eThekwini Deputy Mayor Philani Mavundla says the housing concerns of flood victims have nothing to do with the municipality. eNCA's Manqoba Mchunu reports. #DStv403 DURBAN - eThekwini Deputy Mayor Philani Mavundla says the housing concerns of flood victims have nothing to do with the municipality. Mavundla also told protesters that they’ll gain nothing by occupying the Durban City Hall. WATCH: KZN flood victims occupy Durban City Hall He said the municipality does not have the necessary funds and provincial and national government must deal with it. Flood victims say they will not leave City Hall until they’re given a place to stay. "As a city, we've proved a community hall and opened soup kitchens, beyond that there's nothing we can do," Mavundla said. READ: KZN Floods | Insurance companies have received thousands of claims "Their concerns are genuine, and government needs to intervene. The conditions are not conducive for any human being. The situation is out of our hands. "We've done our best to ensure there's land available to build their homes. National government said we should reprioritise and that's our understanding of reprioritisation." * eNCA's Manqoba Mchunu reports.